    "content": "The second research objective of this paper was to identify\nthe strategies and techniques that can be utilised to mitigate\nAI-driven cyberattacks. The SLR revealed a growing body\nof research on defensive AI against AI-driven cyberattacks.\nIn this section, we synthesised these findings, providing a\ncomprehensive overview of the state-of-the-art approaches\nto safeguarding against the vulnerabilities introduced by\noffensive and adversarial AI. Table 7 summarises the strat-\negies and techniques to combat AI-driven cybercrimes.\nAfter outlining the various defensive AI strategies and\ntechniques to mitigate the risks of AI-driven cyberattacks,\nit is equally important to explore the motivations behind\nthese sophisticated attacks. Understanding the underlying\nTable 5   Types of offensive AI cyberattacks\nAfter exploring the various offensive AI attack types listed in Table 5, it is crucial to dive deeper into a specialised subset of this category: adver-\nsarial AI attacks. These sophisticated attacks exploit the vulnerabilities of ML models, as listed in Table 6\nAuthor\nOffensive AI cyberattack\n[6]\nAudio and video impersonation (Deepfakes); Tailored phishing; Large-scale blackmail; AI-driven malware; Password-based attacks\n(through RNN and GAN); AI capabilities for circumventing mobile security systems\n[27]\nAI-driven social engineering—deception and phishing; AI-driven misinformation and fake news; AI-driven hacking—forgery: deep-\nfakes, repetitive tasks, malware, etc.; Autonomous weapons system\n[15]\nCryptanalysis attack; Side channel attack; Traffic analysis attack; Social network attack; Replay attack; Code injection attack; Cloning\nattack; Sybil attack; Spoofing attack; Black hole attack\n[28]\nAI-driven public opinion manipulation; AI-driven warfare\n[10]\nUse of AI for criminal activities; evasion attacks; poisoning attacks; exploratory attacks\n[64]\nPoisoning attacks, e.g. injection of malicious data or modification of training data; Exploratory attacks, e.g. Membership inference,\nproperty inference, or model extraction; Evasion attacks, e.g. Confidence reduction, misclassification, target misclassification, and\nsource-target misclassification\n[3]\nIntelligent target profiling; Intelligent collection; Intelligent malware; Outcome prediction; Automated payload generation/phishing;\nPassword brute-force attack; Password guessing; Password stealing; Intelligent captcha attack and manipulation; Smart fake review\ngeneration; Intelligent concealment and evasive malware; Behavioural analysis to find new ways to exploit; Automated disinforma-\ntion generation; Intelligent self-learning malware; Automated domain generation; Intelligent DDoS attack\n[91]\nAI-driven price-fixing and collusion; AI-driven spoofing; AI-driven insider dealings\n[93]\nHighly-tailored or AI-based phishing attacks; Automated drones for criminal activity; AI-driven DDoS attack; AI-authored fake news\nand false reviews; AI-assisted stalking and forgery; Terrorism using military robots; Snake oil cryptographic method; AI-assisted\nstalking and forgery\n[4]\nAttack adaptation; Attack coordination; Next-hop targeting; Phishing campaigns; Point of entry detection; Record tampering; Cam-\npaign planning; Persistent access; Malware obfuscation; Virtualisation detection; Biometric spoofing; Cache mining; Implicit key\nlogging; Password guessing; Side-channel mining; Reverse engineering; Vulnerability detection; Mining OSINT (Open Source\nIntelligence); Model theft; Spying; Identity theft; Persona building; Spear phishing; Target selection; Tracking; Covering tracks;\nEvading malware detectors; Evading network IDS; Evading insider detectors; Evading email filters\n[5]\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) attack; Structured query language (SQL) injection attack; Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS); Data\nexfiltration; Autonomous intelligent malware\n[94]\nMisinformation bots; Deepfakes for voice and video spoofing\n[95]\nDeepfakes; Human impersonation through AI-driven bots; Voice cloning\n[14]\nData misclassification; Synthetic data generation; Data analysis for offensive cyber operations; Vishing through audio deepfake; Jam-\nming audio-activated devices\n[88]\nData poisoning; Personalized decoy attacks based on key personal information (social engineering attacks)",
