    "content": "AI and Ethics (2025) 5:883–910\nTable 6   Types of adversarial AI cyberattacks\nAuthor Adversarial AI cyberattack\n[6]\nData poisoning; Disruption of AI-controlled systems; Chatbots creating privacy risks and resulting in data leakage; Fake input data into\nAI engines; AI capabilities for circumventing mobile security systems\n[27]\nIntegrity attacks; Unintended outcomes; Algorithmic trading/stock market manipulation; Membership inference attacks\n[15]\nFalse data injection attack; Jamming attack; White-box, Gray-box, and Black-box attacks\n[10]\nUse of AI for criminal activities; evasion attacks; poisoning attacks; exploratory attacks\n[64]\nPoisoning attacks, e.g. injection of malicious data or modification of training data; Exploratory attacks, e.g. Membership inference,\nproperty inference, or model extraction; Evasion attacks, e.g. Confidence reduction, misclassification, target misclassification, and\nsource-target misclassification\n[91]\nAI-driven spoofing\n[92]\nPoisoning training data; Adversarial inputs; Model extraction attacks\n[93]\nData poisoning; Online eviction; Burglar bots; Adversarial perturbations; AI-assisted stalking and forgery\n[4]\nPoison ML datasets; Plant backdoors in models; Modify surveillance footage; Tamper with medical scans; Ability to evade detection in\nsurveillance; Ability to affect forecast models; Manipulate financial records; Locate vulnerabilities in both source code and compiled\ncode efficiently; Side-channel attacks; Stealing credentials through acoustic and motion side channels; Extracting latent information\nfrom encrypted web traffic; Tracking users through organization’s social media\n[5]\nSample data poisoning; Evasion attacks; Autonomous intelligent malware\n[13]\nEvasion attacks; Poisoning attacks; Domain generation algorithms (DGAs)\n[16]\nTraining data poisoning; Adversarial inputs or evasion attacks; Theft of algorithm software code from the ML model itself\n[94]\nMisinformation bots; Deepfakes f