    "content": "The first research objective of the study was to identify the\ndifferent ways in which AI can be used to launch cyberat-\ntacks. In this section, we used ChatGPT to identify patterns\nand recurring themes in the Table 5 and 6 datasets and to\ngroup them according to the MITRE ATT&CK Framework\nstages. This grouping is shown in Fig. 2.\nBefore discussing the analysed offensive AI data in Fig. 2,\nlet's take note of the following:\n•\t The MITRE ATT&CK Framework stages in Fig. 3 are\nnot necessarily sequential and attackers may skip or\nrepeat stages of an attack, depending on their objectives\nand the victim's environment.\n•\t Some attack types can be categorised in multiple stages\nof the MITRE ATT&CK Framework, and their classifi-\ncation may vary depending on the context. For example,\npassword stealing and password guessing can serve dif-\nferent roles in the cyberattack lifecycle. Attackers can\nTable 9   Societal impact of AI-driven cyberattacks\nAuthor Societal impact of cyberattack\n[6]\nDirect losses; Indirect losses; Operational disruptions; Financial disruption\n[27]\nImpact on data security; Impact on personal safety; Impact on political stability\n[28]\nEconomic costs; Impact on intellectual property; Personal and financial security; Productivity loss; Reputational damage\n[10]\nMedical errors; Transportation risks\n[3]\nLife-threatening consequences; Systemic failures; Erosion of public trust; Economic disruptions; Medical misdiagnoses; Environmental\nrisks\n[4]\nThreat agents such as cyber terrorists, cyber criminals, employees (insiders), hacktivists, nation states, online social hackers, script\nkiddies, competing organisations, non-target specific agents (botnets, worms) target organisations. These agents pose various levels of\nthreats to the organisations themselves, their employees, customers, and potentially to the general public\n[5]\nImpact on privacy and personal security\n[16]\nLoss of privacy; Identity theft; Data breach incidents; Financial loss for business organisations; Infrastructure damage\n[94]\nInadequacy in legal frameworks; Obstacles in investigating cybercrime\n[14]\nCatastrophic military implications; Political disruptions; Compromise of personal and financial information; Traffic accidents in\nautonomous cars; Incorrect medical diagnoses; Erroneous recommendations; False diagnostics in medical imaging; Security bypass in\nnetwork systems\n[88]\nSignificant losses to defenders\nFig. 2   A schema of offensive AI attacks",
